const int mod = 1e9 + 7;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector<int> p(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) cin >> p[i];

    // Create a graph of size n
    vector<vector<int>> g(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        for (int j = i + 1; j < n; ++j) {
            if (p[j] > p[i]) {
                g[i].push_back(j);
                g[j].push_back(i);
            }
        }
    }

    // Find the number of cyclic permutations
    int ans = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        if (g[i].size() >= 3) {
            ans = (ans + (ll)pow(g[i].size(), 2)) % mod;
        }
    }

    cout << ans << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This solution reads from standard input and writes to standard output. It uses a graph representation to count the number of cyclic permutations. The graph is created by iterating over all pairs of indices and adding edges if the condition `p[j] > p[i]` holds. The number of cyclic permutations is then calculated by summing up the squares of the sizes of the cycles. The result is taken modulo \(10^9 + 7\).

