bool isIdempotent(const std::string& filter) {
    // Convert the filter string to a bitset
    std::bitset<128> bits(filter);

    // Apply the filter twice
    bits ^= bits;
    bits ^= bits;

    // Check if the result is the same as the original
    return bits == bits;
}

int main() {
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(std::cin, line)) {
        if (line == "#") break;

        std::string filter = line.substr(1); // Remove the '#' character

        if (isIdempotent(filter)) {
            std::cout << "yes" << std::endl;
        } else {
            std::cout << "no" << std::endl;
        }
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This solution reads a series of filter strings from standard input, applies each filter twice, and checks if the resulting bitset is the same as the original. If they are the same, the filter is idempotent; otherwise, it is not. The `main` function processes each line of input, applies the filter, and outputs "yes" or "no" based on the result.

