#include <algorithm>

int maxPairs(int n, std::vector<int>& a, int m, std::vector<int>& b) {
    // Sort the arrays to make it easier to find the maximum difference
    std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
    std::sort(b.begin(), b.end());

    int count = 0;
    int i = 0, j = 0;

    // Iterate through both arrays
    while (i < n && j < m) {
        // If the current pair's difference is at most 1, increment the count
        if (std::abs(a[i] - b[j]) <= 1) {
            count++;
            i++;
            j++;
        } else {
            // If the current pair's difference is more than 1, move to the next pair
            if (a[i] > b[j]) {
                j++;
            } else {
                i++;
            }
        }
    }

    return count;
}

int main() {
    int n, m;
    std::cin >> n >> m;

    std::vector<int> a(n);
    std::vector<int> b(m);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cin >> a[i];
    }

    for (int i = 0; i < m; ++i) {
        std::cin >> b[i];
    }

    int result = maxPairs(n, a, m, b);
    std::cout << result << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a function `maxPairs` that takes three vectors as input: `a`, `b`, `n`, and `m`. It first sorts these vectors to facilitate finding the maximum difference between corresponding elements. Then, it iterates through both vectors simultaneously, checking if the difference between corresponding elements is at most 1. If it is, it increments the count of valid pairs and moves to the next pair. If the difference is more than 1, it moves to the next pair. Finally, it returns the count of valid pairs. The `main` function reads the input values, calls the `maxPairs` function, and prints the result.

